T2 68 PTBarnum : The native coordinate system is not a euclidean grid.
T2 69 PTBarnum : Think of the pulsars as being clocks that are continuously broadcasting their local time.
T2 70 PTBarnum : The 4 spacetime coordinates they define are just the values of those 4 clocks.
T2 71 PTBarnum : In order to normalize this, I need to choose a 0 point for each clock, and the authors chose the values of the clocks as observed in Cambridge at the beginning of the millenium.
T2 72 PTBarnum : Apparerently, by observing the signals, I can decide how much time to the nearest 4 ns had elapsed at each pulsar, at the time it broadcast the signal I'm now receiving.
T2 73 PTBarnum : I can then define a transform that maps those 4 numbers into whatever local coordinate system I want.
T2 74 PTBarnum : I could convert it to longitude/lattitude/UTC for terrestrial navigation, or some sort of heliocentric system for planetary navigation, or a galactic system for interstellar navigation.
