T2 79 evanbd : It makes the problem more complicated, but it does not add error.
T2 80 evanbd : You don't think the GPS satellites are stationary, do you?
T2 81 evanbd : The source of error here is uncertainty in the measurements of those positions.
T2 82 evanbd : And it actually isn't that bad -- start your spacecraft near Sol, with position well enough defined that you know which pulse you're receiving.
T2 83 evanbd : When observing, you can only see the relative phasing of the pulsars, unlike GPS satellites which transmit a time base.
T2 84 evanbd : Then you need to count pulses as you move.
T2 85 evanbd : You then know that, relative to your starting point or, equivalently, the epoch, you've seen X0 pulses from pulsar 0, X1 from pulsar 1, etc.
T2 86 evanbd : Knowing how many pulses closer to each of the pulsars you are tells you how far you are from your starting point in spacetime, not just space, obviously.
T2 87 evanbd : The error bars get larger as you move enough to get parallax effects -- since from Earth we can only measure the distance to a pulsar with modest precision, and its velocity perpendicular to us with even less.
T2 88 evanbd : If, however, you have a radio telescope that can resolve the position of the pulsar with good precision, you get to add a long baseline parallax measurement to correct for that.
T2 89 evanbd : Add a timebase transmitter at Earth as well, and the errors basically disappear -- errors of a few nanoseconds should be readily available.
T2 90 evanbd : And once you're far enough away from Sol to make that transmitter difficult more than a few lightyears, you'll know the pulsar trajectories well enough it won't matter as much.
T3 91 Anonymous14 : Quoting from Wikipedia wikipedia.org:Relative position of the Sun to the center of the Galaxy and 14 pulsarsThe radial pattern on the left of the plaque shows 15 lines emanating from the same origin.
T3 92 Anonymous14 : Fourteen of the lines have corresponding long binary numbers, which stand for the periods of pulsars, using the hydrogen spin-flip transition frequency as the unit.
T3 93 Anonymous14 : Since these periods will change over time, the epoch of the launch can be calculated from these values.The lengths of the lines show the relative distances of the pulsars to the Sun.
T3 94 Anonymous14 : A tick mark at the end of each line gives the Z coordinate perpendicular to the galactic plane.If the plaque is found, only some of the pulsars may be visible from the location of its discovery.
T3 95 Anonymous14 : Showing the location with as many as 14 pulsars provides redundancy so that the location of the origin can be triangulated even if only some of the pulsars are recognized.The data for one of the pulsars is misleading.
T3 96 Anonymous14 : When the plaque was designed, the frequency of pulsar "1240" now known as J1243-6423 was known to only three significant decimal digits: 0.388 seconds.
T3 97 Anonymous14 : The map lists the period of this pulsar in binary to much greater precision: 100000110110010110001001111000.
T3 98 Anonymous14 : Rounding this off at about 10 significant bits 100000110100000000000000000000 would have provided a hint of this uncertainty.
T3 99 Anonymous14 : This pulsar is represented by the long line pointing down and to the right.The fifteenth line on the plaque extends to the far right, behind the human figures.
T3 100 Anonymous14 : This line indicates the sun's relative distance to the center of the galaxy.
