T8 207 AJNeufeld : That the pulsars move relative to each other and us is true - but this is an extremely minor point.
T8 208 AJNeufeld : The pulsars all have very large masses, which means it would take something HUGE to alter their trajectory significantly.
T8 209 AJNeufeld : Until that happens, that large mass translates to very predictable movement.
T8 210 AJNeufeld : The periodicity of the pulsar is more problematic.
T8 211 AJNeufeld : With a sudden introduction of mass, or a sudden readjustment in the matter of the pulsar, the frequency can abruptly change.
T8 212 AJNeufeld : And yet, this isn't even so much of an issue.
T9 213 AJNeufeld : The pulsars will be monitored from some location Earth or otherwise, and changes to their behaviour can be uploaded to the Galactic Positioning System receivers shortly after the change is observed.
T9 214 AJNeufeld : The receivers might compute positions incorrectly in the interim, but more likely "dead reckoning", combined with other pulsar observations could be used to determine the erroneous input, and ignore it until the update.
T9 215 AJNeufeld : A more serious "flaw" is that the pulsar emissions are not at first blush "marked" with an emission time.
T9 216 AJNeufeld : One pulse looks more or less like the next.
T9 217 AJNeufeld : If a pulse occurs once-a-second, this translates to 300,000 km between pulse fronts.
T9 218 AJNeufeld : If your positioning space exceeds this length, you might end up with ambiguity in your resulting position calculation.
T9 219 AJNeufeld : The other 3 pulsars will provide constraints, making certain "single pulse off-by-one" errors easily discarded.
T9 220 AJNeufeld : But as your location space grows, it becomes more than possible for multiple location solutions to a given set of pulse-front timings.
T9 221 AJNeufeld : With Earth's GPS system, each satellite's transmission is coded with both a satellite identifier and timing information, making this type of error impossible.
T9 222 fireman_sam : Road side maps will no longer have the big sticker "You are here" to mark your location but would have a big sticker "You are here, right now" to mark your position in space time.
